<LP>
   VEHICLE SALES PLUMMETED in the U.S. last month. North
American-made car and truck sales fell 21% in late August.
Overall sales of domestic and imported vehicles for the month
fell 17% from the 1989 period. The drop reflects consumers'
uncertainty about the softening U.S. economy amid the Mideast
crisis.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   World oil supplies are shrinking due to the Mideast
crisis. A U.S. official said shortages could appear by the
middle of the fourth quarter.
   ---
   Franklin Savings' takeover by the government was rejected
by a federal judge, who ordered that control of the
institution be returned today to its previous management.
                                                                                                       

   The House banking chief proposed drastic cuts in deposit
insurance.
   ---
   Prosecutors in the Milken case will attempt to present to
a U.S. judge their full case against the former Drexel
executive, even though the government accepted a plea bargain
to six charges tied to unlawful trading. Ivan Boesky and
others may be called to testify to buttress the government's
bid for a stiff sentence.
   ---
   Both parties are divided internally over deficit-reduction
plans, and the gulf between the Republicans and Democrats
appears as great as ever.
   ---
   The dollar fell sharply as investors bet that tomorrow's
jobs data will push the Fed to cut interest rates. Stocks and
bonds closed higher.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices fell again on fears that futures
settlements next week could spark a massive sell-off. The
Nikkei Index plunged 829.30 points, or 3.3%, to 24078.34.
   ---
   Alex. Brown &amp; Sons plans to nearly double its New York
City presence. The Baltimore-based brokerage firm has been
recruiting brokers from Wall Street rivals.
   ---
   The Kuwaiti asset-management agency in London opened a
multibillion-dollar lending facility to ease Kuwaiti banks'
liquidity problems.
   ---
   College football and ABC Sports are the targets of a
complaint the FTC plans to file today, alleging antitrust
violations in a TV contract.
   ---
   The FDA demanded that Ralston-Purina and five other firms
justify their health claims about oat bran.
   ---
   The Fed effectively crippled a Delaware law that was
expected to allow big banks to sell insurance nationwide. The
move was aimed at a Citicorp unit's business, but banking
officials say it will also bar other banks from taking
advantage of the law.
   ---
   IBM unveiled its long-awaited next generation of
mainframes, which will face competition from new models from
Hitachi and Fujitsu.
